</tbody></table>";}i:217;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:315:"<strong>I say Spanish, You say Spanglish:</strong> The United States‚Äô growing Hispanic community is producing something totally unexpected: a new variety of Spanish. It‚Äôs not Spanglish‚Äîit‚Äôs American Spanish. In 2014, the first words of American Spanish will enter the dictionary of Spain‚Äôs Royal Academy. ";}i:218;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:414:"<strong>A Look at Spanish Though Names:</strong> The name Espa√±a originally meant ‚Äúland of the rabbits‚Äù in Phoenician. Its modern form actually came from French. A look at the different names for Spanish speakers‚Äîfrom Hispanic, Hispano, Latino and Chicano, to Spaniard, Castilian, Spanish and <i>hispanounidense</i>‚Äîreveals the fascinating influences that forged the Spanish language through its history. ";}i:219;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:347:"<strong>The United States‚Äô Spanish Roots:</strong> Discussions about Hispanics in the U.S. inevitably turn to immigration. Yet few understand how deeply the influence of Hispanic culture runs in the United States. Many fundamental features of Americana, from the dollar sign and barbecues, to cowboy culture and mustangs, are of Spanish origin. ";}i:220;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:386:"<strong>French on the Rise:</strong> News of the death of French has been greatly exaggerated. In the last decade alone, the world got 20 million more French speakers.  Though many see French as a language in decline, in fact, it is growing and spreading‚Äînotably in Africa. Though it only ranks ninth in number of speakers, French is still the world‚Äôs second international language.";}i:221;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:407:"<strong>The Other Side of the French Language:</strong> Mention of ‚ÄúFrench‚Äù brings to mind highbrow culture and language police. But the French language has another life as a popular tongue. In the 33 countries where it is an official language, French is evolving and adapting to new realities‚Äîfrom the suburbs of Paris to the backwoods of Louisiana, to classrooms in Quebec and libraries in Africa.  ";}i:222;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:335:"<strong>What makes the French so French:</strong> With their fascination with grandeur and lofty ideas, their fondness for fine food, their hedonism, and supposed arrogance, the French fascinate as much as they mystify. Yet the French have created a society that uniquely suited to the values France has forged over its long history.  ";}i:223;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:327:"<strong>The Riddles of France:</strong> Whether is the Islamic veil, labor riots or globalization, France adapts to political, cultural and economic challenges its own way, maintaining its unique personality and values in the process. In many ways America‚Äôs ‚Äúalter ego‚Äù, France really does represent something ‚Äúelse.‚Äù";}i:224;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:327:"<strong>The Riddles of France: </strong>Whether is the Islamic veil, labor riots or globalization, France adapts to political, cultural and economic challenges its own way, maintaining its unique personality and values in the process. In many ways America‚Äôs ‚Äúalter ego‚Äù, France really does represent something ‚Äúelse.‚Äù";}i:225;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:308:"<strong>How Major Languages Go Global:</strong> Believe it or not, French, Spanish, Arabic and even English all started out as obscure tongues spoken in remote places. Why do some languages spread and turn into global tongues? Politics, economics and even geography explain why languages grow and go global. ";}i:226;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:297:"<strong>What‚Äôs the Best Language to Learn?:</strong> English? Spanish? Mandarin? French? It‚Äôs not just a question of numbers, or countries where they are spoken. The ‚Äúbest‚Äù language to learn depends on what you want to do with it. And some languages have surprising hidden qualities . . . ";}i:227;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:176:"<strong>The Pitch of Your Life:</strong> Writing Non-fiction Book Proposals A step-by-step process to writing a book proposal that literary agents and publishers will jump on. ";}i:228;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:15:"speeches_speech";s:10:"meta_value";s:188:"<strong>Everything Writers Need to Know about Marketing:</strong> From pitching stories, to negotiating fees, how to get published in books, magazines and newspapers‚Äîand get paid for it.";}i:229;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:77:"Visit Julie Barlow and Jean-Beno√Æt Nadeau‚Äôs official website to learn more";}i:230;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:57:"Read a profile of Barlow and Nadeau in The New York Times";}i:231;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:53:"Read The New York Times review of The Story of French";}i:232;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10:"meta_value";s:17:"www.macmillan.com";}i:233;O:8:"stdClass":3:{s:7:"post_id";s:3:"969";s:8:"meta_key";s:23:"related_links_link_name";s:10